First rewrite everything over a common denominator or use the half‐angle form of the second term.  Here is the common‐denominator approach:

\[
\frac{\cos t}{\sin t} + \frac{\sin t}{1+\cos t}
= \frac{\cos t\,(1+\cos t)}{\sin t\,(1+\cos t)} \;+\;\frac{\sin^2 t}{\sin t\,(1+\cos t)}
\]
\[
=\frac{\cos t + \cos^2 t + \sin^2 t}{\sin t\,(1+\cos t)}
=\frac{\cos t +1}{\sin t\,(1+\cos t)}
=\frac{1}{\sin t}
=\csc t.
\]

Hence the given expression simplifies to 
\[
\boxed{\csc t},
\]
provided \(\sin t\neq0\) and \(1+\cos t\neq0\).
